title: Legal rights for egg and sperm donors

heading_context: Legal rights for egg and sperm donors
chunks.html_content:
If you’re a sperm donor, you could be the legal parent of any child born from your donation.

If you donate sperm through a Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) licensed clinic, you will not:

  • be the legal parent of any child born
  • have any legal obligation to any child born
  • have any rights over how the child will be brought up
  • be asked to support the child financially
  • be named on the birth certificate
chunks.plain_content:

Sperm donors
If you’re a sperm donor, you could be the legal parent of any child born from your donation.
If you donate sperm through a Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) licensed clinic, you will not:

  be the legal parent of any child born
  have any legal obligation to any child born
  have any rights over how the child will be brought up
  be asked to support the child financially
  be named on the birth certificate

heading_context: Legal rights for egg and sperm donors
chunks.html_content: If you use an unlicensed clinic to donate sperm, you will be the legal father of any child born from your donation under UK law.
chunks.plain_content:
Legal rights for egg and sperm donors
Sperm donors
If you use an unlicensed clinic to donate sperm, you will be the legal father of any child born from your donation under UK law.

heading_context: Legal rights for egg and sperm donors
chunks.html_content: If you give birth to a child, you’re always considered the legal mother in UK law even when using a donated egg.
chunks.plain_content:
Legal rights for egg and sperm donors
Egg donors
If you give birth to a child, you’re always considered the legal mother in UK law even when using a donated egg.
